The period subsumes from the overarching periods defined for Roman Noricum ("Early Period," "Imperial Period," and "Late Antiquity"; derived from Hagmann 2021, <http://n2t.net/ark:/99152/p0s84tq>). Furthermore, this overarching period takes into account the early pre-occupation activities in the area of the urban settlement at the Magdalensberg ("Stadt auf dem Magdalensberg", Carinthia/AUT), the beginning of which is put around 50 BC (cf., Gassner et al. 2002–2003, 70. 369). Finally, in addition to the absolute early period, the highly late period between 488 and 500 AD is also considered, in the context of which, according to "classical" doctrine and in view of the written tradition (vita Sancti Severini), 488 AD a settlement of the remaining Roman population (so-called "Romanen" in German-speaking research) should have already taken place and which represents a historically highly ambiguous period during the transition to the early Middle Ages (cf., Eichert - Richards 2022, <http://n2t.net/ark:/99152/p0cwwzn>).

properties.spatial_coverage_description: Parts of central continental western Europe
properties.editorial_note:
This period is used by the ArkeoGIS and ArkeOpen projects, in the framework of a general chronology from the Paleolithic to the present day, of a central-western part of continental Europe. It is based on the periodization set up by INRAP and PACTOLS.
The territory covered by this chronology extends from the eastern part of France in the west to Moldavia in the east, and from the south of the UK through southern Germany to Slovenia and central France on a north/south axis.

Cette période est utilisée par les projets ArkeoGIS et ArkeOpen, dans le cadre d'une chronologie générale du Paléolithique à nos jours, d'une partie centrale-occidentale de l'Europe continentale. Elle se fonde sur la périodisation mise en place par l'INRAP et PACTOLS.
Le territoire recouvert par cette chronologie s'étend de la partie orientale de la France, à l'ouest, jusqu'à la Moldavie à l'est, et du sud du Royaume-Uni en passant par l'Allemagne méridionale jusqu'à la Slovénie et le centre de la France sur un axe nord/sud.
